## Data model (key tables)
- **User** — staff/admin accounts. Fields include `full_name`, `email`, `password` (hashed), `role` (free-text label, no longer a fixed enum), `branch_id`, `is_active`, `permissions` (nullable JSON array — see Permissions section below).
- **Branch** — clinic locations.
- **Doctor** — linked to one or more branches.
- **Service** — services offered, shown on the public site.
- **Appointment** — bookings made through the public site or created by staff.
- **ContactMessage** — submissions from the public "Contact us" form.
- **Content** — freeform JSON content per public-site page (home/about/contact/services/projects), edited via the admin Web Editor.
- **Patient, Project, Partner** — supporting tables for the public site's content.

## Authentication flow
1. `POST /api/auth/login` — validates credentials, returns `{ user, token, refreshToken }`. `token` is a short-lived JWT carrying `id`, `email`, `role`, `branch_id`. `user` includes the account's **effective permissions** (see below).
2. Every protected request sends `Authorization: Bearer <token>`. The `authenticate` middleware verifies the JWT, then **re-loads the user from the database on every request** (rather than trusting the token's stale role/permissions) — so a permission change or deactivation by an admin takes effect on the user's very next request, without waiting for their token to expire.
3. `POST /api/auth/refresh-token` — exchanges a valid refresh token for a new access token.
4. `GET /api/auth/me` — returns the current user's profile (used by the admin frontend on page load/refresh to restore the session).

## Permissions system
Two independent things live on every `User` row:
- **`role`** — a free-text label (e.g. "Reception", "Nurse Coordinator"). Purely descriptive today; it no longer restricts what an account can do by itself.
- **`permissions`** — a nullable JSON array of permission strings that determines actual access.

Permission strings in use:
```
manage_doctors      view_doctors
manage_services      view_services
manage_branches      view_branches
manage_appointments  view_appointments
manage_content       view_content
manage_staff
view_contact_messages
view_dashboard
view_notifications
```
"Manage" implies full CRUD; "view" is read-only. Staff management and Contact Messages only have a single tier — there's no separate "view-only staff" or "manage contact messages" concept.

**`User.getRolePermissions(role)`** (in `models/User.js`) — a hardcoded lookup table of default permissions for the handful of legacy fixed role names (`hospital_admin`, `branch_manager`, `content_editor`, `reception_officer`, `marketing_officer`). This exists purely for backward compatibility with accounts created before the `permissions` column existed.

**`User.getEffectivePermissions(user)`** — the single source of truth for what a user can actually do:
- `super_admin` → everything, unconditionally.
- Non-empty custom `permissions` array set → **use exactly that array** (authoritative — does not also fall back to role defaults).
- Otherwise → fall back to `getRolePermissions(user.role)`.

This function is called in two places: building the login/`getMe` response, and inside `authenticate` middleware when populating `req.user.permissions` for every request.

## Authorization middleware (`middleware/auth.js`)
- **`authenticate`** — verifies JWT, loads user, rejects if inactive, attaches `req.user` (including effective permissions).
- **`requirePermission(...perms)`** — route guard; passes if `req.user` has *any one* of the listed permissions (OR semantics), or is `super_admin`. Otherwise responds `403`.
- **`authorize`/`checkRole` (`middleware/roleCheck.js`)** — an older, coarser guard that checks `req.user.role` against a fixed allow-list (`SUPER_ADMIN`, `HOSPITAL_ADMIN`, etc.). Still used on a few sensitive endpoints (creating/deleting staff accounts) where only the two "admin" roles should ever be allowed, regardless of custom permissions.
- **`restrictByBranch`** — attaches a branch filter to the request for branch-scoped managers (not fully wired into every controller yet).

## API routes overview
All routes are mounted under `/api`.

| Resource | Base path | Public routes | Protected routes (permission required) |
|---|---|---|---|
| Auth | `/auth` | `POST /login`, `POST /refresh-token` | `GET /me`, `POST /logout`; `POST /register` (admin roles only) |
| Users/Staff | `/users` | — | Full CRUD + activate/deactivate (admin roles only via `checkRole`) |
| Appointments | `/appointments` | `POST /` (public booking), `GET /reference/:ref` | `GET /`, `GET /:id`, `GET /calendar`, `GET /stats`, `GET /export/pdf` (`view_appointments` **or** `manage_appointments`); `PUT /:id`, `PATCH /:id/status`, `DELETE /:id` (`manage_appointments` only) |
| Branches | `/branches` | `GET /`, `GET /:id` | `POST /`, `PUT /:id`, `DELETE /:id` (`manage_branches`) |
| Doctors | `/doctors` | `GET /`, `GET /:id` | `POST /`, `PUT /:id`, `DELETE /:id` (`manage_doctors`) |
| Services | `/services` | `GET /`, `GET /:id` | `POST /`, `PUT /:id`, `DELETE /:id` (`manage_services`) |
| Content | `/content` | `GET /:page` (feeds the public site + admin live preview) | `POST /:page` (`manage_content`) |
| Contact/Inquiries | `/inquiries` | `POST /` (public contact form) | `GET /`, `PUT /:id` (`view_contact_messages`) |
| Dashboard | `/dashboard` | — | `GET /stats` (any authenticated user) |
| Departments | `/departments` | `GET /` (static list) | — |
| Health check | `/health` | `GET /` | — |

Doctor/Service/Branch listings are intentionally public (unauthenticated) because the public website needs them too — the `view_x` permissions only gate what shows in the *admin* UI, not the public API.

Appointments are the one resource where reads are also gated server-side, since booking data is sensitive (patient names/contact info) — see the "Known bugs already fixed" note below.

## Known bugs already found & fixed in this codebase
1. **Login response wasn't using effective permissions** — `authService.js`'s `publicUser()` was calling `getRolePermissions(json.role)` instead of `getEffectivePermissions(user)`, discarding any custom permissions on login.
2. **Appointments router blanket-required `manage_appointments`** on every route including reads — meaning a view-only account got 403'd just trying to list appointments. Fixed by requiring `view_appointments` OR `manage_appointments` on the GET routes, and keeping `manage_appointments` only on the write routes (PUT/PATCH/DELETE).

## Running locally
1. Create a MySQL database matching `DB_NAME`.
2. Copy the env vars above into a `.env` file at the project root.
3. `npm install`
4. Run the seeders (`src/seeders/initialAdmin.js`) to create the first super admin account.
5. Start the server (entry point should point at `src/` — confirm your `package.json`'s `main`/`start` script, since this project's `server.js` currently has some stale references left over from an earlier CommonJS version and may need reconciling with the ESM `config/database.js` setup actually in use).
